article.headline: Harrison's free throw provides winning margin
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lisa Harrison made one of two free throws with
20.7 seconds remaining as the Phoenix Mercury beat the Washington
Mystics 70-69 in double overtime Sunday.

Anna DeForge led the Mercury (5-19) with 14 points, while Kayte
Christensen had 13.

"Look at our team, and look at the record," Phoenix coach John
Shumate said. "I think most coaches when they scout us, tell their
team to not take this team for granted because these people are
scrappers and they play hard.

"So I try to keep these ladies up and keep them moving forward
so that as we go forward they understand that it's going to get
better, but it starts with us right now."

Reserve center Tuvic Slobodanka gave the Mercury a 69-67 lead
with 52 seconds remaining, but Jocelyn Penn drove the lane to tie
it at 69 with 38 seconds left. Then Harrison was fouled and made
one free throw to give the Mercury the lead back.

Penn then missed the final shot for Washington, giving Phoenix
the victory.

"It just didn't fall," Mystics coach Marianne Stanley said.
"We wanted her to take the shot or draw the foul. We didn't get
the foul and the ball didn't drop."

Penn finished with a team-high 13 points and nine rebounds off
the bench, and Aiysha Smith added 10 points.

"We had too many turnovers," Stanley said. "If we could have
had six or seven turnovers, it could be a different game. If we
shoot even 65 or 70 percent (from the free-throw line), it could be
a different game."

Washington (6-20) played without star forward Chamique
Holdsclaw, who injured her neck Friday night against Connecticut.
Guard Coco Miller, the team's second-leading scorer, saw limited
action with an ankle injury.

Stacey Dales-Schuman scored four straight points in the first
overtime to give Washington a 58-54 lead with 1:45 left. But
Harrison and Christensen each made a basket to tie it at 58 with 47
seconds remaining.

Asjha Jones, who replaced Holdsclaw in the starting lineup,
missed the final shot of the first overtime to send the game to the
second extra period.
